1.Rxf5 {%02 (Now black has a choice, so we need to realize the forcing moves for black: Re5, gf, Ng4, Qe1)}
{%03(Let's find the candidate-moves for white here. First we need to look at the
moves Qa8, Qe8 and Qf6 quickly. These moves looks bad, but anyway we should
check ALL the possible fircing moves. You will spend a little time on it, but
sometimes it will help you to find the winning move. IMPORTANT: you need to
turn off your critique! And look at ALL the forcing moves! In this position
these moves don't work.  Next we should calculate Rf5, Ng6, Nf7, Nf3.)}
gxf5 {%02 (The forcing moves white has here are: Nf7, Ng6, Nf3, g3. It make sense to
think about every move for a second, while finding the candidate-moves. Because
sometimes it will help you to realize which move looks the best, so you will calculate it first.)}
( 1...Qxe1 2.Qxf6+ {%02 it is obviously good for white - white has a material advantage and a strong attack}
) ( 1...Ng4+ 2.Nxg4 Rxe1 3.Qxa8+ $18 ) ( 1...Rxe5 {%02
 (the forcing moves for white here: Qa8, Qf6, Re5. But Qa8 certainly looks like
the best move, because it simply win the rook with check)} 2.Qxa8+
Kg7 3.Rfxe5 Ng4+ {%02 (we need to calculate till the end of the forcing line)}
4.Kh1 Nf2+ 5.Kg1 Nxh3+ 6.gxh3 Qg3+ 7.Qg2 $18 ) 2.g3 {%02
 (AGAIN: you should find ALL the candidate moves for you and for your opponent
as well. To make it - focus your attention on every single piece and ask
yourself which forcing moves it can make. Moves candidates for black here: Qg5, Qh6, Rac8, Ng4)}
( 2.Nf7+ Kg7 {%02 gives nothing for white} ) ( 2.Ng6+ hxg6 {%02 also bad}
) Rac8 {%02 (Now white has a choice. The forcing moves are: Qc8, Qe8, gh, Nf7)}
( 2...Qg5 {%02 (or Qh6)} 3.Nf7+ {%02 fork, winning the queen} )
( 2...Ng4+ 3.Nxg4 {%02 and the black's queen and the rook is under the attack}
) 3.Qd6 ( 3.gxh4 Rxc6 4.Nxc6 Rxe1 $19 ) ( 3.Qxc8 Rxc8 4.gxh4
Rxc5 $15 ) ( 3.Qxe8+ Nxe8 ( 3...Rxe8 4.gxh4 $18 ) 4.gxh4 Rxc5
5.Nf7+ Kg7 6.Rxe8 Kxf7 $15 ) ( 3.Nf7+ Kg7 {%02
 including of this check doesn't change something really, it is still bad for
white. When all the forcing moves don't work we should start to think about the
simple moves. Regarding to the simple moves - white need to move away the queen
and keep an attack on the f6 knight. So white can simply play Qd6} )
Rcd8 {%02  (After Qd6, the moves Qg5 and Qh6 are still bad, cause of Nf7 fork. Now white
has a choice again. The moves-candidates are: Qd8, Nf7, gh)}
4.Nf7+ ( 4.gxh4 Rxd6 5.Nf7+ Kg7 6.Nxd6 ( 6.Rxe8 Rd2+ 7.Kg3 Nxe8
$19 ) Rxe1 $19 ) ( 4.Qxd8 Ng4+ ( 4...Rxd8 5.gxh4 $18 ) 5.Kg2
Qxd8 6.Nf7+ Kg7 7.Nxd8 Rxe1 8.hxg4 fxg4 {%02 and the position is unclear}
) Kg7 5.Nxd8 Ng4+ ( 5...Rxd8 6.Qe7+ Kg8 7.gxh4 $18 ) 6.Kg2 Qxd8
7.Qxd8 Rxd8 8.hxg4 $18 {
 This example shows very well how important to realize all the
moves-candidates. Using this method we was able to find a lot of sudden moves for both opponents.}
( 8.Ne6+ $18 ) 1-0

