1.d7 {%03(The moves candidates for white here are: Qa1 (check) and d7 (threatening d8=Q). First we should calculate check.)}
( 1.Qa1+ f6 2.d7 {%02 (the only attacking move)} Qe7
( 2...d2 3.d8Q Qxf1+ 4.Qxf1 $18 ) 3.Qd4 {%02
 (now black has a choice, so we should find the moves-candidates for black. To
find them - we should focus an attention on the white's territory and think how
can black bring the pieces on this territory and take something or attack something.)}
Qe2 {%02 (threatening Qf1 and Rc1 mate. The moves candidates for white here are: Qa1 (it gives a draw) and Rb1)}
4.Rb1 d2 5.Qxf6+ {%02 (check)} Kxf6 6.d8Q+ Qe7 {%02
 The position is very complicated with a lot of possible lines. To calculate
them we need to spend a lot of time. In the situations like this it make sense
to look at another move-candidate in the initial position first. Probably we
can win after that move easily and it will make no sense to make the long calculation of another line}
) Qxf1+ ( 1...d2 {%02 (the moves candidates for white: Qf8, Qa1, d8=Q)}
2.Qa1+ f6 3.d8Q Qxf1+ 4.Qxf1 {%02 winning} ) 2.Kxf1 d2 {%02 (The moves-candidates are Qf8, Qa1, Qf3, d8=Q)}
3.Qxf3 ( 3.Qf8+ Kxf8 4.d8Q+ Kg7 5.Qd4+ Kh7 6.Qh4+ Kg8 7.Qd8+
{%02 with perpetual check} ) ( 3.Qa1+ Kh7 4.Qh8+ Kxh8 5.d8Q+
{%02 it is the same draw} ) ( 3.d8Q Rc1+ 4.Qxc1 dxc1Q+ 5.Qd1
Qxd1# ) Rc1+ {%02 (The moves candidates: Kg2, Ke2, Qd1)} 4.Qd1
( 4.Kg2 d1Q 5.Qxd1 Rxd1 $19 ) ( 4.Ke2 d1Q+ $19 ) Rxd1+ 5.Ke2
Rb1 ( 5...Re1+ 6.Kxd2 $18 ) 6.d8Q ( 6.Kxd2 Rb8 $19 ) d1Q+ 7.Qxd1
Rxd1 8.Kxd1 {%02 white is up a pawn in the endgame, so it is winning} 1-0

