1.Nxe5+ {%03
 (Usually we should think about the position in general first, and then
calculate the concrete lines. But when you can see the contact between the
pieces (when they are attacking each other) - you should mainly calculate the
lines.  This position is certainly tactical. So we should start the
calculation. The candidate-moves for white here are: Qh5, Ne5, Nh6, Bc5. First
we will calculate checks, because they are the most forcing moves. Comparing
Qh5 and Ne5 we should analyze Ne5 first, once again - because it is the most
forcing move: after that black only can take the knight, while after Qh5 black
has a lot of possibilities. We are starting from the most forcing move, because it is the simplest way.)}
fxe5 {%02 (The moves-candidates now are Qd7 and Bc5. Comparing these 2 moves we should
calculate Bc5 move first, because it is the most logical move: white is winning
the material, intending to win the black's queen then.)} 2.Bxc5
( 2.Qd7+ Be7 3.Bc5 Rg2+ 4.Kh1 Rf2+ 5.Kg1 Qg2# ) Rc1 {%02 (The white's move candidates are: Qd7, Qh5, Rc1)}
( 2...Rg2+ 3.Qxg2 $18 ) 3.Qh5+ Ke6 4.Qxf3 Bxf3 5.Rxc1 $18 {
 The conclusions: 1. We should calculate the most forcing and logical moves
first. 2. While finding the moves-candidates it makes sense to think about
every move for a second. It helps to realize which move looks the best, so you
will calculate it first. This will help you to save your time.} 1-0

